    summary: 'Lily of the valley (Convallaria majalis) is a small perennial woodland plant native to Eurasia, producing arching stems lined with tiny white bell-shaped flowers. Despite its delicate appearance, it has one of the most famous fragrances of any flower and a place in royal weddings going back over a century — Princess Grace, Princess Diana, and Kate Middleton all carried it.',
    meaning: 'Lily of the valley symbolises the return of happiness, sweetness, motherhood, and humility before joy — the pendant flowers are seen as bowing in modesty. In Christian tradition the flower is associated with the tears of the Virgin Mary at the cross (one of its folk names is "Mary\'s tears"), and white lily of the valley is a major wedding bloom representing pure love. In France, May 1 is "La Fête du Muguet": tradition holds that giving a sprig of lily of the valley to family and loved ones brings a year of good luck — a custom said to date to 1561 when King Charles IX received a sprig and decided to gift one annually to every lady at court.',
